article.description:
The Phoenix Mercury turned an emotional day into
a victorious night hours after coach Cynthia Cooper resigned.

related.description: Cynthia Cooper resigned as coach of the Phoenix Mercury hours before the team's game against the Seattle Storm on Wednesday.
related.linkText: Cooper steps aside as coach of Mercury after 1½ seasons
related.title: Mercury elevate assistant Sharp to interim coach
related.headline: Mercury elevate assistant Sharp to interim coach

article.headline: Harrison has career night for interim coach
article.linkText: Cooper's resignation sparks Mercury over Storm
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- The Phoenix Mercury turned an emotional day into
a victorious night hours after coach Cynthia Cooper resigned.

	   Lisa Harrison tied a career high with 22 points and had 10
rebounds to lead the Mercury past the Seattle Storm 62-53 Wednesday
night.

	   "You can't ignore what just happened,'' Harrison said. "But we
had to focus on the game and we had to beat Seattle.''

	   Cooper, who was 19-23 less than 1½ years into her first head
coaching job, met with team president Bryan Colangelo and general
manager Seth Sulka before the game.

	   "I decided that the best thing for me, my family and the
organization as a whole was for me to step down,'' Cooper said in a
statement.

	   Harrison said it was distracting to learn about Cooper's
resignation before the game, but it may have had a positive effect.

	   "We were playing with emotion,'' Harrison said.

	   Sulka reiterated after the game that Cooper decided to step down
after the meeting. Harrison said later that she understood Cooper
had resigned and wasn't fired.

	   Linda Sharp took over as interim coach.

	   Sharp was 1-1 as a fill-in after Cooper left June 14, the day
before her twins were about to be delivered by a surrogate mother
in Houston. Cooper returned June 21 in a game at Houston and
coached Sunday and Tuesday before resigning Wednesday.

	   "I thought their players would be extremely motivated for their
new coach,'' Seattle head coach Lin Dunn said.

	   Sharp was surprised by the move.

	   "I had no idea,'' she said. "She called me this afternoon. I
think potentially she is a really good coach and I think she will
get back into it one day. We have to move forward. I never ever
expected to be in this situation.''

	   During Wednesday night's game, Harrison scored 14 points in the
second half, including six during a key 8-0 run midway through the
half and assisted on the other basket.

	   Seattle got within 53-51 with 2:45 left after trailing most of
the night. But the Storm missed on their next possession and then
lost the ball when Gordana Grubin tied up Sue Bird and Phoenix won
the jump ball.

	   Jennifer Gillom made 3 of 4 free throws and scored a layup in
the final minute to help the Mercury pull away. She added 20 points
and Adrain Williams had 12 rebounds for Phoenix.

	   "I'm embarrassed at the way we defended Jennifer Gillom when
she put the ball on the floor and drove to the basket,'' Dunn said.

	   Lauren Jackson had 13 points and Bird added 11 for Seattle.

	   Simone Edwards added 11 points and six rebounds for the Storm.
